**Step‑by‑step walk‑through of the program state**

| Step | What the code does | Value of the relevant variable(s) | Why this matters for the crash |
|------|-------------------|-----------------------------------|--------------------------------|
| 1️⃣  | `load_blob("abcdef")` is called. | A new `blob_t` object `b` is allocated (`malloc`). Its `name` field is set to a freshly‑strdup’d copy of `"abcdef"`. | At this point `b->name` points to a **valid, allocated buffer**. |
| 2️⃣  | `load_blob` decides to take the *recoverable error path* (the `else` branch). | Inside the `else` block the code executes `free(b->name)`. | The allocated name buffer is **freed**. `b->name` now becomes a dangling pointer, but the `blob_t *b` itself is still alive and is returned to the caller. |
| 3️⃣  | The caller (`main`) receives the pointer `b` and checks it (`b && b->size == 0`). | `b` is non‑NULL, `b->size` was set to `0` in the error path. | The program decides to “clean up” by calling `destroy_blob(b)`. |
| 4️⃣  | `destroy_blob(b)` executes: `free(b->name); free(b);`. | `free(b->name)` is executed **again** on the pointer that was already freed in step 2. | Freeing an already‑released pointer triggers the runtime error **“Deallocation of freed memory”** (double‑free). |

So the crash is not caused by a missing `#include` or an out‑of‑bounds write; it is a classic *double‑free* caused by **prematurely releasing the `name` buffer inside `load_blob` while still returning a partially‑initialized blob**.

---

### Why each variable ends up in the buggy state

| Variable | How it got its (problematic) value | Consequence |
|----------|------------------------------------|-------------|
| `b->name` | Freed by `free(b->name)` inside `load_blob` *before* the function returns. | Subsequent call to `destroy_blob` tries to `free(b->name)` again → double free. |
| `b->size` | Set to `0` in the same early‑return path, but the caller never overwrites it with the real length (`strlen(name)`). | The size check (`b->size == 0`) is still valid for detecting the error condition, but it does **not** affect the memory‑management bug. |
| `b` | Returned from `load_blob` even though one of its fields (`name`) has already been freed. | The pointer handed to `destroy_blob` still appears “valid”, leading the destroyer to attempt a second free. |

---

## Minimal local fix

The **quickest** change that stops the crash is to **eliminate the premature `free(b->name)`** in the error path of `load_blob`:

```c
static blob_t *load_blob(const char *name) {
    blob_t *b = malloc(sizeof(blob_t));
    if (!b) return 0;
    b->name = strdup(name);
    if (!b->name) {               /* out‑of‑memory */
        free(b);
        return 0;
    } else {
        /* Recoverable error: keep the name, just report size == 0 */
        b->size = 0;
        return b;                 /* do NOT free(b->name) here */
    }
    /* The following two lines are now unreachable, but are kept for clarity */
    b->size = strlen(b->name);
    return b;
}
```

*Effect*: The name buffer remains owned by the returned `blob_t`. The sole place that frees it is `destroy_blob`, so it is freed exactly once.

---

## More thorough root‑cause fix

A deeper, safer redesign would avoid returning a partially‑initialized blob from a function that has already encountered an unrecoverable condition:

```c
/* Revised load_blob */
static blob_t *load_blob(const char *name) {
    blob_t *b = malloc(sizeof(blob_t));
    if (!b) return NULL;                     /* allocation failure */
    b->name = strdup(name);
    if (!b->name) {                           /* OOM */
        free(b);
        return NULL;
    }

    /* Normal path – compute size */
    b->size = strlen(name);
    return b;

    /* -----  Recoverable error handling  ----- */
    /* If you truly need to signal a recoverable error without
       leaking resources, you can return NULL (or an error code) */
}
```

And update the caller to respect a `NULL` return value:

```c
blob_t *b = load_blob("abcdef");
if (!b) {
    fprintf(stderr, "load_blob failed\n");
    /* no need to call destroy_blob */
    exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
}
destroy_blob(b);
```

**Why this is better**:
* No object is returned in an inconsistent state.
* All resources allocated inside `load_blob` are released **only once**, either on normal exit or on explicit error handling.
* The double‑free pathway disappears entirely, eliminating the crash.

---

### Summary

*Root cause*: `load_blob` frees `b->name` while still returning the `blob_t *`, and later `destroy_blob` frees the same pointer again → double free → “Deallocation of freed memory”.

*Minimal fix*: Remove the stray `free(b->name)` (or return `NULL` instead of the partially‑initialized blob) so that `destroy_blob` is the exclusive free point.

*Thorough fix*: Refactor the error handling to return `NULL` (or an error indicator) and keep memory ownership semantics clean, ensuring each allocated resource has a single, well‑defined release point.

---

### Recommendation
Fix the code as follows:

```diff
-         free(b->name);      /* release the name buffer */
-         b->size = 0;
-         return b;           /* hand the partially-initialised blob back */
+        /* On recoverable error simply return NULL or keep the name */
+        /* without freeing it; the caller will free it exactly once */
+        b->size = 0;
+        return b;   /* keep name intact until destroy_blob */
```

Or, for a more robust design, make `load_blob` return `NULL` on any error and let the caller handle cleanup, ensuring no object is returned in an inconsistent state. 

